		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
<div><p>We present neutron powder diffraction results which give unambiguous evidence for the formation of the recently identified new crystalline ice phase [4], labeled ice XII, at completely different conditions. Ice XII is produced here by compressing hexagonal ice I h at T = 77, 100, 140 and 160 K up to 1.8 GPa. It can be maintained at ambient pressure in the temperature range 1.5 &lt; T &lt; 135 K. High resolution diffraction is carried out at T = 1.5 K and ambient pressure on ice XII and accurate structural properties are obtained from Rietveld refinement. At T = 140 and 160 K additionally ice III/IX is formed. The increasing amount of ice III/IX with increasing temperature gives an upper limit of T ≈ 150 K for the successful formation of ice XII with the presented procedure.</p></div>
			</abstract>
		</profileDesc>
